\begin_layout Section
Interventions and Experimental design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both experiments are implemented using short videos that were shown to farmers
 on tablet computers.
 The videos were designed with a dual purpose in mind.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, the videos serve to transfer knowledge about new recommended agronomic
 management practices and the use of modern technologies.
 It is shown how fields need to be prepared using organic fertilizer, and
 proper seed spacing and seeding rates.
 It is shown in detail how inorganic needs to be applied and in what quantities.
 Furthermore, detailed attention is devoted to identifying striga, a parasitic
 weed that affects maize yields in the area.
 Other recommended practices include timely planting and weeding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, the information was packaged as an inspirational story of poor farmers
 that, over time, are able to break out of a poverty trap.
 The video starts with a farmer explaining that he used to struggle with
 low yields, producing barely enough food to feed his family, but that over
 the years, he learned how to increase the number of bags of maize produced
 on his maize plots.
 It is shown how the farmer starts using recommended practices on a small
 part of his land.
 It is also shown how he sells a chicken and borrows some money from a neighbour
 to buy improved seed and fertilizer.
 The extra money from this initial investment is then re-invested, and the
 viewer is taken through some basic inter-temporal cost-benefit calculations.
 The video ends by showing a happy farmers that assures that the viewer
 can also become a successful farmer by following his example.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first research question, whether reducing agricultural extension information
 asymmetries within the household improves outcomes, will be answered by
 comparing outcomes of households in which one adult individual (husband
 or wife) is shown a video to outcomes of households in which the couple
 (husband and wife together) is shown a video with the same information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first research question, whether promoting a household approach to farming
 improve outcomes at the household level, will be answered by comparing
 outcomes of households that are shown a video where the messenger is an
 individual farmer (ie.
 a man or a women) to outcomes of households that are shown a video providing
 the same information by a couple of farmers (ie.
 man and woman who are shown to participate as equals in the family farm
 and deliver the message as a couple).
\end_layout

