\begin_layout Section
Implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We confirm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "doss2014owns"

\end_inset

 that little difference in the share of men and women who participate in
 four agricultural decisions: what crops to grow, what inputs to use, what
 to sell, and who keeps the revenue from sales.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Couples disagree about the unilateral decision making, but agree about joint
 decision making.
 Joint decision making is the prevailing mode of decision making
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We see that decision making patterns are similar across management practices,
 but that men are more likely to make decisions related to the use of modern
 inputs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
information seems to be shared less if targeted to the wife only.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
women within the household have insufficient agency to implement knowledge
 gained, which is consistent with the decision making pattern in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Joint-decision-making"

\end_inset

.
 As a result, from a policy perspective, it is important to include the
 husband in extension campaigns if the focus is on household level adoption
 of new practices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Agricultural household models do not behave as a unit.
 Outcomes are a result of bargaining over scarce resources.
 However, a focus on individual level outcomes has resulted in policies
 and projects focusing too much on empowering women, often through providing
 them with exclusive control over resources.
 This exclusive focus on women may bring about adverse effects including
 jealously and distrust in the household, in some cases leading to domestic
 violence, husbands withdrawing from providing for the household as they
 feel less responsible, or even reduced women’s decision-making power in
 particular domains 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "de2014impact"

\end_inset

.
 A focus on women’s control over resources risks to move ever further away
 from the essence of empowerment which revolves around balancing power relations
 and which re-lies on shifts in consciousness and changes in structural
 constraints to gender equity (Cornwall 2016).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also refer to this new article in AJE: insights on how women prefer to cooperate
? 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bernhardt2019household"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another advantage is that if the focus is on women empowerment, there is
 only one way in: the woman.
 If the focus is on cooperation, we can work also through the husband.
\end_layout

